<text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
  <body>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="TolE0425">
<l>allatu kiḷappi ṉellā moḻiyuñ</l>
<l>colliya paṇpi ṉiyaṟkai yākum</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
          <l>If followed by other [sounds], it [ = i.e. the <foreign xml:lang="ta">āytam</foreign>]
          disappears.<note place="foot">I.e. when followed by words beginning with non-vowels, e.g. <foreign
                xml:lang="ta">ahtu + ciṟitu &gt; atu ciṟitu</foreign> ' That is small '. The reason for these rules is not clear. According to
            T.P.Meenakshisundaram (A History of Tamil Language, 1965, p. 137) these two rules
            contradict the rule in aphorism 39, and hence he thinks they may be interpolated.
            However, the author in question is, I am afraid, mistaken, for these rules concern
            entirely different morphophonemic changes, cf. my translation of aphorism 39, and note
            35, on pp. 48 and 59 resp. of the first issue of this journal (Sept. 1972).<foreign
                xml:lang="ta"></foreign></note></l>
      </lg>
    </div>
